      "body" : "This was exactly what I needed - to exclude specific fields at runtime."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 5258546,
        "reputation" : 630,
        "user_id" : 4200722,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/SI83x.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "omahdi",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4200722/omahdi"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 3,
      "creation_date" : 1630177526,
      "post_id" : 43168061,
      "comment_id" : 121887121,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "<code>ObjectWriter.withoutAttribute</code> does not work as suggested in the answer. The <i>attribute</i> does not refer to property names of input data and are never referenced in such a context, as pointed in <a href=\"https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-core/issues/700#issuecomment-849182602\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this comment</a>, for example. This method seems to be geared towards internal use, as can be seen <a href=\"https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/blob/2.13/src/main/java/com/fasterxml/jackson/databind/ser/std/StdSerializer.java#L364\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here</a>."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 53471,
      "reputation" : 6073,
      "user_id" : 159837,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/bUdOT.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Fırat K&#252;&#231;&#252;k",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/159837/f%c4%b1rat-k%c3%bc%c3%a7%c3%bck"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 28,
    "last_activity_date" : 1491134400,
    "creation_date" : 1491134400,
    "answer_id" : 43168061,
    "question_id" : 7421474,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Annotation based approach is better. But sometimes manual operation is needed. For this purpose you can use <strong>without</strong> method of <strong>ObjectWriter</strong>.</p>\n\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>ObjectMapper mapper   = new ObjectMapper().configure(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNKNOWN_PROPERTIES, false)\nObjectWriter writer   = mapper.writer().withoutAttribute(\"property1\").withoutAttribute(\"property2\");\nString       jsonText = writer.writeValueAsString(sourceObject);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10953953,
      "reputation" : 429,
      "user_id" : 8049404,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f3a660d056bdaebf76bd12b734d72da0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "fifman",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8049404/fifman"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1544497606,
    "creation_date" : 1544497606,
    "answer_id" : 53716767,
    "question_id" : 7421474,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you want to ALWAYS exclude certain properties for any class, you could use <code>setMixInResolver</code> method:</p>\n\n<pre><code>    @JsonIgnoreProperties({\"id\", \"index\", \"version\"})\n    abstract class MixIn {\n    }\n\n    mapper.setMixInResolver(new ClassIntrospector.MixInResolver(){\n        @Override\n        public Class&lt;?&gt; findMixInClassFor(Class&lt;?&gt; cls) {\n            return MixIn.class;  \n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public ClassIntrospector.MixInResolver copy() {\n            return this;\n        }\n    });\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5448686,
      "reputation" : 7293,
      "user_id" : 4573839,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 89,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/9bv0RbKN.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "yu yang Jian",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4573839/yu-yang-jian"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1728379762,
    "creation_date" : 1728379762,
    "answer_id" : 79065263,
    "question_id" : 7421474,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>in the case if you control/own the code, it is simple use <a href=\"https://www.baeldung.com/jackson-ignore-properties-on-serialization\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>@JsonIgnoreProperties</code></a>:</p>\n<pre><code>@JsonIgnoreProperties(value = { &quot;intValue&quot; })\npublic class MyDto {\n\n    private String stringValue;\n    private int intValue;\n    private boolean booleanValue;\n\n    public MyDto() {\n        super();\n    }\n\n    // standard setters and getters are not shown\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
