  "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/7421474/how-can-i-tell-jackson-to-ignore-a-property-for-which-i-dont-have-control-over",
  "title" : "How can I tell jackson to ignore a property for which I don&#39;t have control over the source code?",
  "body" : "<p>Long story short, one of my entities has a <a href=\"http://www.vividsolutions.com/jts/javadoc/com/vividsolutions/jts/geom/GeometryCollection.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">GeometryCollection</a> that throws an exception when you call \"getBoundary\" (the why of this is another book, for now let's say this is the way it works). </p>\n\n<p>Is there a way I can tell Jackson not to include that specific getter? I know I can use @JacksonIgnore when I do own/control the code. But this is not case, jackson ends reaching this point through continuous serialization of the parent objects. I saw a filtering option in jackson documentation. Is that a plausible solution?</p>\n\n<p>Thanks!</p>\n"
}